				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$B_{\mu \nu }$$\end{document}, whose presence is crucial in gaining the non-commutativity.

In flat space, T-duality relates σ\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\sigma $$\end{document}-derivatives of the coordinates of the original theory with the momenta of its T-dual theory, and vice versa. As the momenta of the original theory are taken to be commutative, it follows that the coordinates commute as well. So, in flat space there is no non-commutativity of the closed string T-dual coordinates. This is in agreement with the fact that T-duality is a canonical transformation in the flat space, and with the fact that PB’s are invariant under such transformations.

